SQL to PySpark — Bridge Pack Description
This project practices moving from SQL thinking to PySpark thinking, using two small tables — customers and orders — joined together to answer seven common business questions.
The data
Two files are used:
•	customers.csv — one row per customer, with an id, name, and city.
•	orders.csv — one row per order, with an id, the customer it belongs to, and an amount.
Each file has one row with a missing customer id, and two customers were given no orders at all, so the cleaning step and the "no orders" exercise both have something real to catch.
Cleaning step
Before anything else, rows with a missing customer_id are dropped from both tables. A missing id can't be matched to anything in a join, so keeping it around would either silently disappear in later steps or cause misleading results.
The seven exercises
For every exercise, the same question is answered twice: once written as plain SQL, and once written using PySpark's DataFrame methods. Running both side by side makes the mapping between the two languages easy to see.
#	Exercise	Approach
1	Total order amount for each customer	Inner join + SUM, grouped by customer
2	Top 3 customers by total spend	Same as #1, sorted descending, limited to 3
3	Customers with no orders	Left join, keep rows where the order side is empty
4	City-wise total revenue	Inner join + SUM, grouped by city
5	Average order amount per customer	Inner join + AVG, grouped by customer
6	Customers with more than one order	Inner join + COUNT, grouped by customer, filtered to count > 1
7	Sort customers by total spend descending	Left join so zero-order customers are included, then sorted
The key idea: inner join vs. left join
Most exercises only care about customers who actually placed an order, so an inner join is enough. But exercise 3 (no orders) and exercise 7 (sort everyone by spend) specifically need customers with zero orders to still show up — an inner join would quietly drop them. A left join keeps every customer, and any customer with no matching order simply gets empty or zero values.
What this shows
Together, the exercises cover the core relational skills that come up constantly in real data work: joining two tables, grouping and summarizing, filtering before and after aggregation, and choosing the right join type depending on whether missing matches should be kept or dropped.
